# 37Metrics — Cursor Core Rules

## Behavior

- PLAN first, code second. For any task touching more than 2 files, explain your approach and wait for confirmation.
- Make the smallest change that solves the problem. Do not refactor unrelated code.
- NO ASSUMPTIONS. Read the relevant file before acting. Missing info? Search the codebase, then ask.
- CHALLENGE bad ideas. If you see a flaw or a better approach, say so directly.
- LOG CHECK. After any code change or bug fix, verify terminal/console output before declaring done.
- RULE REFRESH. Re-read this file every few messages in long sessions.
- Do not apologize for errors — fix them.
- If code is incomplete, add a `// TODO(your-name): description` comment.

## Tech Stack

- **Web:** Vite + React + TypeScript + React Router + Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui
- **Server state:** TanStack Query (React Query)
- **Client state:** Zustand
- **Forms/Validation:** React Hook Form + Zod
- **HTTP:** Axios
- **Dates:** date-fns / date-fns-tz
- **Icons:** Lucide React
- **Node APIs:** Express or Fastify
- **Python APIs:** FastAPI + Pydantic
- **Python CLI:** typer or click + rich
- **Desktop:** Tauri (Rust + React)
- **Package manager:** npm only — never Yarn, pnpm, or Bun
- **Python deps:** Poetry for projects; pip + requirements.txt for scripts
- **Testing (JS/TS):** Vitest + Playwright
- **Testing (Python):** pytest
- **DB (primary):** PostgreSQL (local, Docker, or managed cloud) — **SQLite** is fine for personal apps and local tools
- **DB (document):** MongoDB (self-hosted)
- **DB (serverless):** DynamoDB when you are on AWS

## Naming (Apply Automatically)

- Repos: `37m-{project-name}` kebab-case
- Branches: `feature/`, `fix/`, `hotfix/` in kebab-case
- Commits: Conventional Commits — `feat(scope): description`
- React components, classes, interfaces: PascalCase
- Variables, functions: camelCase; hooks use `use` prefix
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
- Python: snake_case for files/folders/functions/variables; PascalCase for classes
- SQL: snake_case columns and tables (plural); views prefixed `vw_`
- MongoDB: camelCase fields and collections (plural)
- Environment variables: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE; Vite browser vars use `VITE_` prefix

## TypeScript

- `"strict": true` always — never disable
- No `any` — use `unknown` with type guards or generics
- Prefer `interface` over `type` for object shapes
- `async/await` over raw Promises; always `try/catch`
- Explicit return types on all exported/public functions

## Code Style

- Write self-documenting code — name things well, do not comment what code does, comment why
- Keep files under 300 lines — split when it improves clarity
- Handle errors and edge cases at the top of functions (guard clauses / early returns)
- Keep the happy path last
- No deeply nested conditionals — use early returns
- Imports: keep them alphabetically sorted
- SOLID principles — separation of concerns without over-engineering

## API Standards

- URL pattern: `/api/v1/resources` — version from day one
- Error shape: `{ status, message, code, details? }`
- Every API needs `GET /health` → 200
- JSON logging with request ID, timestamp, user context
- CORS: explicit allowed origins only — never `*` in production
- Validate all input — Zod (Node.js) or Pydantic (Python)
- Default pagination: `limit=20`, max `limit=100`; return `{ data, total, page, limit, hasMore }`

## Database

- Store all dates in UTC; use ISO 8601 in APIs
- Schema changes via migration tools only (Prisma Migrate, Drizzle Kit, Alembic)
- Never edit an already-applied migration — create a new one
- Index all WHERE, JOIN, and ORDER BY columns
- Select only needed columns — never `SELECT *` in production

## Security

- TLS 1.2+ on all connections
- Secrets via environment variables, OS keychain, 1Password CLI, GitHub Actions Secrets, or AWS Secrets Manager — never hardcoded
- Least privilege on all DB and API connections
- Never log passwords, tokens, or PII
- MFA on admin operations where the service supports it

## What Never to Do

- No `.env` commits — only `.env.example` with placeholders
- No `any` in TypeScript
- No Next.js, Remix, Angular, Yarn, pnpm, or Bun without a documented reason in the project README
- No hardcoded credentials anywhere
- No migrations that edit already-applied migration files

## Git (solo / personal)

- Use feature branches when they help review or CI; direct commits to `main` are fine for solo repos if you prefer
- On shared remotes, protect `main` and use PRs when collaborating

## Memory bank (when present)

- If `.memory-bank/README.md` or `.memory-bank/INSTRUCTIONS.md` exists, read it before substantial feature work or architecture changes.
- Use `.memory-bank/*.md` for condensed, persistent project context; refresh those files when decisions or phase of work changes materially.
- Do **not** treat the memory bank as a substitute for reading the codebase and tests.

## Project Structure Reference

```
# React / Vite
src/components/   # Shared UI components
src/components/ui # shadcn/ui components
src/features/     # Feature modules
src/hooks/        # Shared hooks
src/lib/          # Utilities, API client, constants
src/pages/        # Route-level pages
src/types/        # Shared TS types

# Node.js API
src/routes/       # Route definitions
src/handlers/     # Controllers
src/services/     # Business logic
src/middleware/   # Auth, validation, error handling
src/models/       # DB schemas
src/types/        # TS types
src/utils/        # Shared utilities
```

## Common Commands

```bash
# Node.js
npm install && npm run dev
npm run test
npm audit

# Python
poetry install && poetry run python src/main.py
poetry run pytest

# Git
git checkout develop
git checkout -b feature/your-feature-name
git commit -m "feat(scope): short description"
```

